  "prompt": "What happens to the photons when I switch off the light?",
  "response": "When you switch off the light, photons are no longer being emitted by the light source. Photons are particles of light, and they are produced by sources such as light bulbs, LEDs, or other luminous objects. When the source is turned off, the emission of new photons ceases.\n\nThe photons that were emitted before you turned off the light will continue to travel until they are absorbed or scattered by objects in their path. If there are no objects to absorb or scatter them, they will continue to propagate through space. In a typical room, photons are usually absorbed by walls, furniture, and other objects, converting their energy into heat or other forms of energy.\n\nIn summary, switching off the light stops the emission of new photons, and the existing photons are either absorbed or scattered by their surroundings.",
